WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.790
&gt;&gt; Hi, guys.
Thank you so much for coming to today's author

00:00:06.790 --> 00:00:12.330
talk.
Today, we have Emily Nagle Green, who is the

00:00:12.330 --> 00:00:14.630
president and CEO of the
Yankee group.

00:00:14.630 --> 00:00:17.970
And she wrote this great book called "Anywhere",
about global

00:00:17.970 --> 00:00:23.109
connectivity and business initiatives that
can really draw a lot of

00:00:23.109 --> 00:00:25.991
value from that increased connectivity in
our world.

00:00:25.991 --> 00:00:29.110
So please welcome Emily Nagle Green to Google
Boston.

00:00:29.110 --> 00:00:31.160
Emily Nagle Green: Thank you.
Thank you.

00:00:31.160 --> 00:00:34.579
I don't need this, I think.
But if anybody wants to talk.

00:00:34.579 --> 00:00:39.780
Oh, you're going to hold on to that.
Okay, cool.

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:46.660
Hi, Google Boston, and hi, Google anywhere.
My name's Emily Green and I'm delighted to

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:51.640
be here.
I have Steve Vinter of Google Boston, Google

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.410
Cambridge to thank for
that.

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:59.059
Steve and I met about a year ago.
We're both on a committee that the governor

00:00:59.059 --> 00:01:04.800
of Massachusetts formed to
get technology leaders in the Boston and greater

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:10.240
Massachusetts area to
help create more energy and enthusiasm around

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:14.590
a very vibrant tech
sector in the Massachusetts area.

00:01:14.590 --> 00:01:19.540
And Steve has exhibited all the great qualities
I have come to know

00:01:19.540 --> 00:01:24.640
about Google as an organization.
And he's also an awesome dodgeball player,

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:25.770
it turns out.
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:25.770 --> 00:01:30.600
Yeah, he hit my husband with a dodgeball but
with incredible accuracy.

00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:36.899
So this is an author talk, and I thought maybe
the easiest way to do it

00:01:36.899 --> 00:01:40.990
-- I have some experience with this now because
the book's been out for

00:01:40.990 --> 00:01:43.770
a few weeks.
I thought I would offer to interview myself

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:46.960
to make it easy for you.
I know this is supposed to be casual, and

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:50.149
it's Friday, we here in
Boston, we have hot chocolate.

00:01:50.149 --> 00:01:52.369
So I thought I would interview myself so that
you can just sort of sit

00:01:52.369 --> 00:01:53.840
back and enjoy the interview.
And you don't have to do any work, really.

00:01:53.840 --> 00:02:01.909
You can eat your croissants and enjoy your
hot chocolate.

00:02:01.909 --> 00:02:05.890
Yes, so I'm told.
The chef says it's his specialty.

00:02:05.890 --> 00:02:09.399
So the first thing I thought I would start
with was, who am I?

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:14.170
I'm a researcher and Yankee Group is a 40,
4-0, 40-year old research

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:17.870
firm that is based here in Boston but is focused
on the global

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:23.230
revolution in connectivity that is underway.
I'm a former engineer.

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:27.050
I started my life as a software developer,
but it was so long ago that

00:02:27.050 --> 00:02:30.950
I would be homeless if I had to go back to
that profession right now.

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:35.500
But I am proud to say that as a software developer,
I spent some time

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:41.690
working in the entertainment industry.
And I am one of the very first generation

00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:46.230
of software developers that
can claim movie credits.

00:02:46.230 --> 00:02:49.580
Back in the early 80s, I worked on some really
fun movies and TV shows

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:52.200
doing special effects.
But my software development days are long

00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:55.069
behind me.
And I'm a researcher and I spent the last

00:02:55.069 --> 00:02:59.300
year with other analysts at
Yankee Group and a lot of other experts in

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:02.530
the industry looking at the
changes that are under way in connectivity.

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:06.380
And it was my view that while a lot of us,
including probably everyone

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:13.040
in this room and everybody on the DVR, is
quite fluent with more

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:17.130
immediate issues that are underway in the
communications revolution.

00:03:17.130 --> 00:03:20.610
There's a much larger audience for that news
out there in the world

00:03:20.610 --> 00:03:24.550
that hasn't yet put some of these changes
into context and doesn't yet

00:03:24.550 --> 00:03:31.280
see the tremendous implications that are ahead.
So let's start with the first question on

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:33.459
my interview list after who
am I.

00:03:33.459 --> 00:03:38.830
And that is what, in fact, is anywhere?
What definition do I give to that word?

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:43.370
I sort of co-opted that term.
That's what industry analysts do, we either

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:47.000
make up words or we borrow
words and use them for our own purposes.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.360
So apologies for that.
But I think it really works.

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:55.080
Anywhere is the term that I've given to the
emergence of ubiquitous

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:59.019
connectivity, how it will connect all of us
on the planet, and

00:03:59.019 --> 00:04:03.049
ultimately -- hi -- all the things that we
care about.

00:04:03.049 --> 00:04:08.650
And I call it anywhere because for my money,
it is completely changing

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:12.440
the meaning of location in two kind of interesting
ways that are

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:16.370
contradictory.
In one sense, as the world is connected by

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:23.700
a pervasive, capable,
extremely cool digital fabric, it doesn't

00:04:23.700 --> 00:04:27.900
so much matter where we are.
So location becomes less significant, but

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:31.910
the information associated
with location becomes much more significant

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:35.851
and much more useful to us
because it can be embroidered and embedded

00:04:35.851 --> 00:04:40.700
in a lot of our activities.
So that's the anywhere revolution and it's

00:04:40.700 --> 00:04:43.070
coming about because of what
I call the anywhere network.

00:04:43.070 --> 00:04:49.060
That's my vision and the vision of Yankee
Group for a seamless --

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:53.721
hardly at that stage today -- intelligent,
sort of headed in the right

00:04:53.721 --> 00:04:59.440
direction; ubiquitous, that is, everywhere;
and abundant network.

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:03.970
We're actually going towards that future.
And in recent years we're accelerating towards

00:05:03.970 --> 00:05:06.450
that future even faster
than we might have imagined.

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:10.500
I like the word abundant for network capacity
and I think it's

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:12.430
particularly relevant within the last -- what
is it?

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:16.220
Twenty four hours since the announcement about
Google's ultra-high speed

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.600
contribution to the network.
So thanks for that.

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:23.440
I'm a big believer in abundance in the network.
One of the people I interviewed for this book

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:28.060
was Bob Metcalfe, who if
you don't know him, is a seminal thinker and

00:05:28.060 --> 00:05:32.181
inventor and leader in the
history of network technology and the phrase

00:05:32.181 --> 00:05:36.750
he uses -- which I have
completely stolen -- is squanderable abundance

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:41.400
of the network.
And I think it's when the network is abundant

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:47.340
to a degree that we can
actually waste it, that's when we're struck

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:51.560
with really compelling
ideas for how to take advantage of it in brand

00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:54.350
new ways.
And you know, the best, most recent example

00:05:54.350 --> 00:05:57.710
of the last few years would
be YouTube, of course.

00:05:57.710 --> 00:06:03.710
So why is this important?
Well, it's important for a lot of us in this

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:06.780
room and on this DVR
because it's creating really interesting work

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:12.600
for us and fun work, but
in the larger question, remember I said I

00:06:12.600 --> 00:06:16.370
wrote the book for the larger
audience that needs to understand how impactful

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:22.370
this transition towards
a global network with squanderable abundance

00:06:22.370 --> 00:06:28.320
is going to be, is that
the changes in this revolution will make it

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:30.800
the largest technology
revolution of all of our lifetimes, even for

00:06:30.800 --> 00:06:35.180
those of you who are among
the -- on the younger end in this room as

00:06:35.180 --> 00:06:39.710
opposed to on the older
end -- this is going to be a transformation

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:42.880
that will dwarf anything
that we've previously seen.

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:47.860
I like to compare it to the largest tech revolution
that I think we've

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:53.000
all been through in some form or another in
our lifetime so far, and

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.080
that's the emergence of the commercial Internet,
which happened

00:06:56.080 --> 00:07:01.420
starting in '95 to 2005.
And when you think about that revolution and

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:04.900
how it emerged, the
locations where it was relevant to us was

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:10.850
where we worked or in our homes or at schools,
but not in a lot of other places.

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:14.710
Even so, it brought a billion people together
in the first ten years of

00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:21.300
its commercial maturity.
And the value added from an economic perspective

00:07:21.300 --> 00:07:24.430
by this brand new
infrastructure that a billion people were

00:07:24.430 --> 00:07:28.750
able to use in essentially
three places was in the billions of dollars.

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:33.470
Because it allowed companies and services
and activities to emerge that

00:07:33.470 --> 00:07:36.330
could not have existed without the Internet.
Hard for the younger people in this audience

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:41.530
today to even imagine,
right?

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:44.360
And then that's what happens with any kind
of pervasive infrastructure.

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:50.270
Highway systems created the hotel industry
in the 50s.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:53.740
The maturation of the professional commercial
television industry

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:59.080
created really what's the modern advertising
industry.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:01.980
Anywhere is a revolution that will connect
not only work, home, and

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:06.890
school but plazas and subways and jungles.
And if you read the story in the New York

00:08:06.890 --> 00:08:10.700
Times this morning about
school buses now starting to experiment with

00:08:10.700 --> 00:08:14.660
adding mobile routers to
school buses so kids can recapture that lost

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:20.130
productivity of commute
time to and from school with wireless routers.

00:08:20.130 --> 00:08:24.600
In the next five years alone, this will mean
that over five billion

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:29.330
people are connected.
And the real thing that's driving that, of

00:08:29.330 --> 00:08:31.860
course, is wireless
technology, because wireless networks are

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:35.760
now coming to parts of the
world that would never have seen connectivity

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:40.150
if it was dependent on
running fixed-line networks with telephone

00:08:40.150 --> 00:08:42.490
poles and fiberoptic and
copper cables.

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:46.940
So five billion people will be connected,
at the very least, through

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:50.550
mobile phone technology which will be for
many of them the only way

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:53.000
that they actually ever touch this digital
network.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:55.250
But more importantly, and I'll come back to
this in a moment, we're

00:08:55.250 --> 00:09:00.660
going to start connecting things in a really
serious way, and that's

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:02.430
where some of the biggest transformation that's
ahead is.

00:09:02.430 --> 00:09:04.830
So as a result of that, the economic value
from this revolution

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:08.590
compared to the emergence of the Internet
in the first ten years, will

00:09:08.590 --> 00:09:12.660
be in the trillions of dollars rather than
in the billions of dollars.

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:17.300
And I know that's true because I'm an expert.
You know what an expert is, right?

00:09:17.300 --> 00:09:20.260
"X" is the unknown quantity and "spurt" is
a drip under pressure.

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:27.070
So an expert is an unknown drip under pressure.
It's an old joke.

00:09:27.070 --> 00:09:32.590
But at Yankee Group, we measure the economic
value of the emergence of

00:09:32.590 --> 00:09:36.530
the broadband network infrastructure around
the world, and this is our

00:09:36.530 --> 00:09:40.090
forecast most recently of the total value
of revenues in the network,

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:44.170
just providing broadband services to consumers
and businesses.

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:48.560
So by 2013, about a billion dollars in value.
But that's the platform itself.

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:52.660
So if we were talking about the highway system,
that would be revenues

00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:56.590
from tolls on the highway.
But when you think about the Googles, the

00:09:56.590 --> 00:09:59.910
YouTubes, the Amazons, all
the experiences that we're going to be able

00:09:59.910 --> 00:10:05.520
to layer on top with assets
like Android, then we're talking about trillions

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:10.080
of dollars of
incremental value on top of that digital global

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:14.280
platform.
So the book is about the emergence of that.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:21.730
It is not a tech book at all.
I wrote it for my mother, your aunts and uncles,

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:26.230
your friends who don't
understand what it is you do.

00:10:26.230 --> 00:10:30.600
It's about how this transformation is inevitable.
It's really not stoppable.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:34.510
But there's a lot of explanation about why
that's true.

00:10:34.510 --> 00:10:38.290
It's about the consequences of ubiquitous
connectivity.

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:41.580
And it's about the tremendous commercial opportunities
associated with

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:45.780
ubiquitous connectivity.
And it does that through some things that

00:10:45.780 --> 00:10:47.830
I hope are friendly and not
intimidating.

00:10:47.830 --> 00:10:54.490
As I said, it's not a deep dive into the technology.
I like to tell people I'm a recovering engineer,

00:10:54.490 --> 00:10:57.090
you know.
I have a -- belong to a 12-step program.

00:10:57.090 --> 00:10:59.810
I have a number I call if I'm tempted to engineer
anything because I'm

00:10:59.810 --> 00:11:03.490
not allowed to do it anymore.
So we do support it with a little data, so

00:11:03.490 --> 00:11:09.060
that we're credible.
But it does involve a lot of anecdotal explanations

00:11:09.060 --> 00:11:11.940
and experience from
over 50 leaders in connectivity.

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:16.390
I'm proud to say, that because I'm part of
a very vibrant community of

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:20.970
technology entrepreneurialism in the Boston
area, that over ten of those

00:11:20.970 --> 00:11:23.560
people were based in the Boston area.
People like Bob Metcalfe, Nicholas Negroponte,

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:27.300
Hamish Fraser, who's the
director of tele-medicine at Partners in Health,

00:11:27.300 --> 00:11:30.800
one of the
organizations that's doing tremendous work

00:11:30.800 --> 00:11:34.760
in Haiti right now.
But beyond that, we created some personas

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:39.410
to make it easy for people to
visualize in five and ten years time how experiences

00:11:39.410 --> 00:11:40.410
would be
different.

00:11:40.410 --> 00:11:42.800
There's some case studies, there is even some
Cosmo quiz style things

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:47.390
that make it more engaging. So the goal was
to make it very accessible

00:11:47.390 --> 00:11:51.580
and fun, but also compelling.
One of the ways in which we do that we tried

00:11:51.580 --> 00:11:56.760
to help people to understand how this
revolution is emerging around the world is

00:11:56.760 --> 00:11:59.090
by means of something
called the anywhere index.

00:11:59.090 --> 00:12:03.810
And very simply put, it's a brute-force instrument
to help people

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:06.790
understand the pace at which broadband that
is emerging around the

00:12:06.790 --> 00:12:09.920
world.
We look at the number of broadband lines in

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:14.830
the world, wired or wireless
lines, and we compare that to population in

00:12:14.830 --> 00:12:18.020
a region.
And when there are fewer broadband lines than

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:22.400
people, that's one state
of play in the network.

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:26.830
And as broadband lines start to increase beyond
the population in a

00:12:26.830 --> 00:12:29.000
region, that's what we call the anywhere tipping
point.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.380
Because the pervasiveness of the cape -- of
a capable network with

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:38.730
squanderable abundance starts to allow innovation
and adoption of

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:45.420
entirely new behaviors and activities.
Um, so this is unfolding before us.

00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:48.510
And these are some, some figures that we update
at Yankee Group on a

00:12:48.510 --> 00:12:51.550
regular basis.
Right now, to use the terms that I just laid

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:57.340
out, regions that have
more than one broadband line per person -- and

00:12:57.340 --> 00:12:59.620
if you think about the
number of things in your life that might ultimately

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:05.230
have broadband
connections, we have very few countries in

00:13:05.230 --> 00:13:06.230
the world that actually meet
that definition.

00:13:06.230 --> 00:13:09.920
And it's a little bit hard to see here in
Boston today, but you can see

00:13:09.920 --> 00:13:16.660
Sweden, and you can see Japan and Korea perhaps,
and Australia are colored as anywhere countries.

00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:17.660
&gt;&gt; [inaudible]

00:13:17.660 --> 00:13:20.290
Emily Nagle Green: Yes, yes.
Yes.

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:26.610
The bar, you know, full disclosure, the bar
for our wireless broadband line,

00:13:26.610 --> 00:13:30.540
the bar is pretty low in our definition, because
we're not really at

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:35.660
the infrastructure and the mobile space that,
you know, 4G broadband,

00:13:35.660 --> 00:13:39.660
that's what we would all like to have.
Maybe 6G.

00:13:39.660 --> 00:13:43.130
But over the next five years, a number of
countries because of the

00:13:43.130 --> 00:13:48.670
build out of wireless networks and upgrades
to 3G as AT&amp;T tries to fix

00:13:48.670 --> 00:13:53.270
it's map relative to Verizon, and as countries
around the world pull

00:13:53.270 --> 00:13:57.960
more fiber from stimulus packages from government,
we see most of

00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:02.210
Western Europe and all of North America in
five years time having a

00:14:02.210 --> 00:14:06.589
total number of broadband lines that will
surpass the population.

00:14:06.589 --> 00:14:10.920
And it's, I think, a good indicator that we're
accelerating into a very

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:14.700
different environment in the next five to
ten years.

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:18.870
How will it change us as individuals?
That's some of what we talk about in the book

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:21.390
in what I think is an
engaging way, that's some of the feedback

00:14:21.390 --> 00:14:27.350
I've had so far.
Just to give you a bit of a taste, a couple

00:14:27.350 --> 00:14:31.990
of personas drawn from the
book, you'd learn more about them as when

00:14:31.990 --> 00:14:36.040
you read it Fatuma is a
coffee farmer in Kenya.

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:40.980
She has tuberculosis, which is extraordinarily
common in emerging

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:44.060
countries, unfortunately, cause we know how
to cure it.

00:14:44.060 --> 00:14:47.200
But at this time a chronic disease that requires
ongoing maintenance

00:14:47.200 --> 00:14:52.000
from a health care worker.
She also doesn't have access to information

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.140
resources that would tell
her how she could price her coffee beans to

00:14:56.140 --> 00:15:00.330
get the best price.
She -- somebody comes up and offers her a

00:15:00.330 --> 00:15:03.580
price for her crop and that's
what she sells it for.

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:07.201
And one of the challenges in compiling assets,
economic assets, in

00:15:07.201 --> 00:15:11.529
Third World markets is she has no access to
banks.

00:15:11.529 --> 00:15:15.970
There are no ATMs and no easy-to-reach banking
resources.

00:15:15.970 --> 00:15:20.440
That's her life today.
In India, where wireless networks are already

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:24.220
more common, in
particular in urban areas like Mumbai, we

00:15:24.220 --> 00:15:26.270
have Habib who's a street
cart merchant.

00:15:26.270 --> 00:15:32.370
He's 15-years old, so he has the basic education
that a lot of lower

00:15:32.370 --> 00:15:37.230
middle class Indians get.
He operates a cart but he has to buy his groceries

00:15:37.230 --> 00:15:42.029
at retail.
He competes for his space on the sidewalk

00:15:42.029 --> 00:15:45.930
every day, so he's worried
about getting the best price for his groceries,

00:15:45.930 --> 00:15:48.470
but he's compelled to
pay whatever he has to so that he can get

00:15:48.470 --> 00:15:52.350
to his spot on the sidewalk.
He has a lot of tourists come by, but they

00:15:52.350 --> 00:15:57.089
haven't changed their money
yet, so he doesn't have a means to do business

00:15:57.089 --> 00:16:01.241
with them because they
have dollars or euros and he only deals in

00:16:01.241 --> 00:16:04.770
rupees.
And because he has cash, he's a very easy

00:16:04.770 --> 00:16:09.279
target for petty thieves.
Finally, in emerging parts of the world, the

00:16:09.279 --> 00:16:15.790
state of the network today
allows people like Allen to do a knowledge

00:16:15.790 --> 00:16:19.380
worker's job, but what he's
really working with is secondhand data.

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:23.870
He's working with data that has been stale
and processed through many

00:16:23.870 --> 00:16:27.180
sources.
And the sources of information he has are

00:16:27.180 --> 00:16:30.649
quite siloed.
You see here that he's looking at multiple

00:16:30.649 --> 00:16:34.170
screens.
And it's the gray matter between his ears

00:16:34.170 --> 00:16:37.570
that's attempting to
integrate the information that's been presented

00:16:37.570 --> 00:16:39.470
to him, and it's mostly
text.

00:16:39.470 --> 00:16:42.240
The work schedule -- he has to work when the
markets are open and he's

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:47.820
basically chained to this desk.
But as the network becomes more pervasive

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:52.980
around the world and as the
capacity of the network grows and its intelligence

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:55.620
grows, everybody's
experience changes in some way.

00:16:55.620 --> 00:16:58.540
For Fatuma, she gets better health care because
organizations like

00:16:58.540 --> 00:17:03.630
Partners in Health can develop medical records
systems that depend on

00:17:03.630 --> 00:17:06.390
network access.
And so, the community health care workers

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:11.390
in Kenya and in Haiti and
Rwanda can find Fatuma, let her know when

00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:15.770
the medications for her
tuberculosis are available, and they can track

00:17:15.770 --> 00:17:19.740
where she lives.
She also can get information about market

00:17:19.740 --> 00:17:25.380
pricing for her crop on a
mobile phone, and she can do banking through

00:17:25.380 --> 00:17:28.240
her mobile phone.
So she's able to build assets and that's a

00:17:28.240 --> 00:17:30.260
life-changing set of
opportunities.

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:34.410
And that will move her, in the next ten years,
and people like her into

00:17:34.410 --> 00:17:39.410
a burgeoning lower middle class in places
like Kenya, which is just now

00:17:39.410 --> 00:17:47.430
being touched by fiberoptic cable undersea.
For Habib, and other citizens like him, he

00:17:47.430 --> 00:17:51.520
will be able to use netbooks
and other low cost computing devices that

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:54.180
will be subsidized or
sponsored by a retailer.

00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:57.760
And he can order product, and so he pick it
up efficiently without

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:02.900
missing his spot on the street corner.
He can earn points from offering mobile couponing

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:06.320
and mobile banking
services, so that he doesn't have to handle

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:10.090
money, and that reduces his
vulnerability to thieves.

00:18:10.090 --> 00:18:14.390
And it's been shown that the introduction
of connected devices like

00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:18.300
laptops, actually dramatically raises the
literacy levels of family

00:18:18.300 --> 00:18:19.300
members around individuals, and that was something
that come out in

00:18:19.300 --> 00:18:26.220
conversations with Negroponte with his one
laptop per child movement.

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:29.390
But in more mature parts of the world that
already have an abundant

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:33.010
network but which is going to continue to
grow in capacity and

00:18:33.010 --> 00:18:36.080
intelligence, what we're headed towards is
knowledge workers like Allen

00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:39.620
who will be able to use integrated highly
visual displays that follow

00:18:39.620 --> 00:18:44.740
him from place to place.
So that he can appear in a new location in

00:18:44.740 --> 00:18:49.929
his back porch or in another
venue and work almost in different to his

00:18:49.929 --> 00:18:54.320
location.
But he'll be working with real time data because

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:57.890
the abundant global
network will be able to bring censor-based

00:18:57.890 --> 00:19:03.470
information to him on crops,
so rather than relying on secondhand informations

00:19:03.470 --> 00:19:07.850
about the maturity of
Fatuma's coffee beans, he'll ultimately be

00:19:07.850 --> 00:19:12.410
able to understand the
maturity of coffee beans from the field-based

00:19:12.410 --> 00:19:14.880
networks themselves.
And he'll be unchained from his desk, and

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:17.500
we'll see a marvelous
flowering -- as we are already starting to

00:19:17.500 --> 00:19:21.240
do in the tech sector --
we'll see a marvelous flowering outside of

00:19:21.240 --> 00:19:25.280
the tech sector of workers
whose jobs are changing, their connections

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:31.420
to the workplace changing,
so that they may be freed and have less conventional

00:19:31.420 --> 00:19:34.410
work hours and
then maybe a less conventional relationship

00:19:34.410 --> 00:19:40.580
with their employers.
So I said I was going to interview myself.

