I told you who I am.
I told you a little bit about Anywhere, the

00:19:44.430 --> 00:19:47.780
emergence of ubiquitous
connectivity; I told you why you should care

00:19:47.780 --> 00:19:48.890
because it's the largest
technology revolution of our lifetimes.

00:19:48.890 --> 00:19:53.840
I told you a little bit about what that change
in pervasive abundant

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:59.700
intelligent network will help people do.
And I talked a little bit about what we hope

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:03.950
the book will do.
So that means I really only have one question

00:20:03.950 --> 00:20:07.780
left which I think I'm
more or less on schedule.

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:09.460
And that is my own initial impression on what
it might mean for

00:20:09.460 --> 00:20:13.820
Googlers?
So I thought I'd take a few moments on that

00:20:13.820 --> 00:20:20.270
before we maybe talk a
little bit about the book, if you like.

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:23.179
You guys are an interesting group of people
because you have a

00:20:23.179 --> 00:20:26.990
fascinating organization.
And this book, frankly, many of you may not

00:20:26.990 --> 00:20:30.550
learn much that you don't
already feel you know about the pace at which

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:33.780
the network's evolving
and the capabilities of the network.

00:20:33.780 --> 00:20:39.059
Remember, we're talking to a much larger audience
about the evolution

00:20:39.059 --> 00:20:42.309
of connectivity.
And this book is an optimistic, encouraging

00:20:42.309 --> 00:20:47.510
future vision of the world
that I hope will enroll more believers in

00:20:47.510 --> 00:20:50.550
what you're doing.
So hopefully, it will enlarge the appetite

00:20:50.550 --> 00:20:57.420
of the world for Google's
incredibly exciting products and expertise.

00:20:57.420 --> 00:21:01.309
But I think more than that, I do think Google
is a company that thinks

00:21:01.309 --> 00:21:05.990
big, tremendously big.
And that's inspiring, but I think it's fair

00:21:05.990 --> 00:21:09.640
to ask given what we saw on
our research about the rate at which the network's

00:21:09.640 --> 00:21:12.740
expanding and its
capacities and future intelligence -- the

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:16.760
question might be are you
sure you're thinking big enough?

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:21.850
Because I think not only are we connecting
more people, we're going to

00:21:21.850 --> 00:21:25.120
have more connected consumers from a billion
to five or six billion.

00:21:25.120 --> 00:21:33.750
But we're going to have new kinds of consumers.
I saw once in a design philosophy statement

00:21:33.750 --> 00:21:39.010
about Google user
interfaces or user experiences that you seek

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:44.680
to meet unarticulated
needs, which I liked, because I often talk

00:21:44.680 --> 00:21:47.340
about the latent appetites
of consumers.

00:21:47.340 --> 00:21:52.330
We are a mobile species.
We were born on our feet.

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:57.270
We learned to walk early on.
And we respond to things that allow us to

00:21:57.270 --> 00:22:01.580
be mobile.
And we love the portability of devices and

00:22:01.580 --> 00:22:05.490
experiences.
And what I see emerging is a new kind of consumer,

00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:09.160
an Anywhere consumer
who has a innate, eventually an innate expectation

00:22:09.160 --> 00:22:11.740
that experiences
should be portable.

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:14.620
And you're starting to make that happen, but
I think there are many

00:22:14.620 --> 00:22:18.000
more experiences that aren't yet quite as
portable as we might like

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:23.760
them to be.
This Anywhere consumer is an Anywhere worker

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:26.860
as well.
And again, in the tech sector we see it is,

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:30.299
I think, well-established
early signs of new behaviors in relationship

00:22:30.299 --> 00:22:34.610
to a workplace.
But over the long term, I think companies

00:22:34.610 --> 00:22:38.840
everywhere will be
transformed by the expectations we -- sorry

00:22:38.840 --> 00:22:43.070
 -- we have as consumers and
employees for state-of-the-art technology

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:47.000
that keeps pace with the
evolution of consumer technologies.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:52.730
Why should our workplace platforms be any
less sophisticated and easy

00:22:52.730 --> 00:22:56.900
to use and fun and flexible as the things
that we can buy for

00:22:56.900 --> 00:23:00.910
ourselves?
And that will change companies as we move

00:23:00.910 --> 00:23:05.520
proprietary hardware and
software out of big IT operations and move

00:23:05.520 --> 00:23:06.530
those things into the
clouds.

00:23:06.530 --> 00:23:12.670
I think anywhere enterprises can be become
more nimble and more

00:23:12.670 --> 00:23:16.220
exciting and a more contemporary workplace,
virtual workplace, for

00:23:16.220 --> 00:23:20.650
employees.
But I just wanted to leave on one final note,

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:23.330
one of the most
interesting things to me personally about

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:28.840
the emergence of ubiquitous
connectivity is the emergence of new kinds

00:23:28.840 --> 00:23:33.740
of connected devices.
I do see within the tech sector -- and I have

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:44.000
been in technology for
35 years, I started, I was just a baby when

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:45.960
I started.
But I do see a little bit of myopia from time

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:51.020
to time.
We get so focused on computers, laptops and

00:23:51.020 --> 00:23:53.940
phones, what's really
happening is connectivity becomes ubiquitous.

00:23:53.940 --> 00:24:00.080
And at the cost of adding connectivity to
things continues to fall,

00:24:00.080 --> 00:24:05.220
we're seeing a lot more connected things.
And there's where Google really needs to make

00:24:05.220 --> 00:24:08.550
sure it's thinking big.
Maybe you've seen some of these -- these are

00:24:08.550 --> 00:24:12.850
all real devices.
This is a connected pill bottle made by a

00:24:12.850 --> 00:24:18.110
company here in Cambridge called Vitality.
And when you take the cap off, it can let

00:24:18.110 --> 00:24:22.640
your friends, your health
care professionals know if you're taking your

00:24:22.640 --> 00:24:26.320
medication.
So it can help maintain a health regimen.

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:30.350
It doesn't do anything else, but it does a
better job of being a pill

00:24:30.350 --> 00:24:36.990
bottle because it's connected.
This is also invented by the same guy, David

00:24:36.990 --> 00:24:39.620
Rose, this is a connected
umbrella.

00:24:39.620 --> 00:24:43.450
It doesn't tell you what the weather is, but
twice a day it can get an

00:24:43.450 --> 00:24:48.390
update on the possibility of precipitation
where you are, and it turns

00:24:48.390 --> 00:24:51.630
that light on in the bottom of the handle
if it's going to rain.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:55.530
So it doesn't tell you the weather but it
does a better job of being an

00:24:55.530 --> 00:24:59.799
umbrella.
It is more "umbrella-ish" because it knows

00:24:59.799 --> 00:25:03.380
when you need it.
You're more likely to have it with you.

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:08.100
This is an active RFID tag, not a very sexy-looking
thing, but the tip

00:25:08.100 --> 00:25:12.100
of the iceberg in terms of something that
I think is very sexy, which is

00:25:12.100 --> 00:25:17.049
equipping assets and businesses and environments
around the world with

00:25:17.049 --> 00:25:22.580
connectivity so they can report on their location,
whether they're wet or dry or broken or complete

00:25:22.580 --> 00:25:28.910
or ready or unready or in some sort of danger.
And as that technology becomes more pervasive

00:25:28.910 --> 00:25:31.960
in our ambient
environment that world is -- that's going

00:25:31.960 --> 00:25:33.990
to flood our world with some
rich data.

00:25:33.990 --> 00:25:38.860
And that's part of the opportunity for an
enterprise like Google to

00:25:38.860 --> 00:25:43.130
organize that.
This is a Bluetooth ring.

00:25:43.130 --> 00:25:47.429
It's a piece of jewelry.
It was just debuted in January at the Consumer

00:25:47.429 --> 00:25:52.510
Electronics Show.
It has an E-ink display, so it can accept

00:25:52.510 --> 00:25:55.710
little text messages and
things.

00:25:55.710 --> 00:25:57.299
And so it can connect to your phone.
And there have been a lot of attempts on connected

00:25:57.299 --> 00:26:01.130
clothing and things.
I think there will be many more experimentations

00:26:01.130 --> 00:26:08.860
ahead with connected
things, some of which will be tragically weird.

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:12.220
And some of us, maybe even some of us in this
room, will be sporting

00:26:12.220 --> 00:26:16.470
those at various events and being reviled
by our friends and family for

00:26:16.470 --> 00:26:22.480
how extremely nerdy they are making us look.
Nonetheless, there are huge transformations

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:23.880
ahead in the meaningfulness
and the functionality of very common devices

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:30.380
in our lives.
I think, if you think back to the emergence

00:26:30.380 --> 00:26:35.250
of a standard electrical
grid in our parents' lives and our grandparents'

00:26:35.250 --> 00:26:39.740
lives, and what that
did, it transformed coffee pots that sat on

00:26:39.740 --> 00:26:41.520
a stovetop into
percolators.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:47.450
It transformed brooms into vacuum cleaners
that we could push.

00:26:47.450 --> 00:26:55.450
It transformed wind-up clocks into wristwatches.
The world was completely transformed by the

00:26:55.450 --> 00:26:57.530
availability of pervasive,
inexpensive electricity.

00:26:57.530 --> 00:27:00.700
And the tools of the our lives were transformed
because electricity

00:27:00.700 --> 00:27:05.150
came to the device in the form of a motor
and made that thing more

00:27:05.150 --> 00:27:10.070
useful to us.
