relative development of developing countries?

00:32:04.570 --> 00:32:06.910
Because I think this will provide a great
amount of opportunity for

00:32:06.910 --> 00:32:10.190
people who are already connected but for countries
who are not even --

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:13.520
not even close to that like how will that
match up?

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:20.450
Like, do you have like a sense of what that
will be?

00:32:20.450 --> 00:32:23.890
Emily Nagle Green: I understand what you're
asking, I think.

00:32:23.890 --> 00:32:27.340
I actually think that it -- at the end of
the day, if we would be able

00:32:27.340 --> 00:32:32.210
to measure the individual benefits that come
from the explosion of a

00:32:32.210 --> 00:32:36.450
ubiquitous global network, it will be greater
for individuals,

00:32:36.450 --> 00:32:40.770
ultimately, outside what we now think of as
the developed regions.

00:32:40.770 --> 00:32:44.250
And the reason is that while they may not
have in ten-years time, they

00:32:44.250 --> 00:32:49.270
may not have a network, a sense of abundance
that's as squanderable as

00:32:49.270 --> 00:32:52.049
we will have.
They may not have been fiber to the home,

00:32:52.049 --> 00:32:57.120
and they may not have 4G or
5G or 6G, they will have the first digital

00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:01.460
infrastructure they've ever had.
And where the digital infrastructure that

00:33:01.460 --> 00:33:06.280
we have here is evolving, it
supplements existing infrastructure.

00:33:06.280 --> 00:33:10.250
I could still get a newspaper on my doorstep
every day until the Boston

00:33:10.250 --> 00:33:15.330
Globe gives up the ghost, right?
And I still have banks that I can go to, I

00:33:15.330 --> 00:33:17.140
have brick and mortar stores
that I can go to.

00:33:17.140 --> 00:33:21.361
So if the Internet melted down tomorrow, I
would be very sad but I

00:33:21.361 --> 00:33:25.990
wouldn't be unable to get on with my life.
I could go to stores and do my banking and

00:33:25.990 --> 00:33:30.320
get my news.
But where the network is emerging, even in

00:33:30.320 --> 00:33:34.480
a more limited form, and
wireless networks through very limited feature

00:33:34.480 --> 00:33:39.159
phones or maybe the very
cheap smartphones, I hope, that's the first

00:33:39.159 --> 00:33:44.320
time people are having
access to information, banking, connecting

00:33:44.320 --> 00:33:45.320
them to the health care
environment.

00:33:45.320 --> 00:33:49.620
So their experience might not be something
that's going to support the

00:33:49.620 --> 00:33:52.890
evolution of four dimensional smell-o-vision
or whatever you guys

00:33:52.890 --> 00:33:57.840
invent next.
It's going to be more life-changing for them

00:33:57.840 --> 00:34:00.250
cause it's going to give
them their first ever opportunity to participate

00:34:00.250 --> 00:34:04.030
in a larger economy.
So I think ultimately the innovations that

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:08.339
will come from getting the
next, you know, 3 or 4 billion people connected

00:34:08.339 --> 00:34:12.200
to the network those
innovations might be more meaningful to all

00:34:12.200 --> 00:34:15.809
of us in society.
And I think the sources of innovation may

00:34:15.809 --> 00:34:20.819
shift from thinking of them
as Silicon Valley and Cambridge and Western

00:34:20.819 --> 00:34:23.940
Europe, and the sources of
innovation might actually be those places

00:34:23.940 --> 00:34:27.559
that are desperate to have
the advantages that they don't have today

00:34:27.559 --> 00:34:31.099
like India, where incredibly
creative things are getting done right now

00:34:31.099 --> 00:34:34.409
with very cheap phones and very limited wireless
networks.

00:34:34.409 --> 00:34:37.359
I don't know if that answers your question.

00:34:37.359 --> 00:34:43.210
&gt;&gt; So I'd be interested to find out, like,
what you see is happening

00:34:43.210 --> 00:34:45.129
with the transfer-open Internet, cause I feel
like a lot of these

00:34:45.129 --> 00:34:48.719
forecasts assume that the network will stay
open and it's not going to

00:34:48.719 --> 00:34:54.960
be throttled and cross-associated with -- so
as a prognosticator, what

00:34:54.960 --> 00:34:57.809
do you see happening in the next couple years
with that?

00:34:57.809 --> 00:35:00.339
Emily Nagle Green: It's a good question, and
I will say that there's

00:35:00.339 --> 00:35:03.569
an entire chapter in the book that deals with
what I would call black

00:35:03.569 --> 00:35:07.589
swans, which are things that could threaten
the assumptions that we

00:35:07.589 --> 00:35:14.890
make at Yankee Group about this happy future.
There's no question that regulation and other

00:35:14.890 --> 00:35:22.640
legislative constraints
could threaten some of the assumptions we

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:23.640
make.
And one of which is that the Internet will

00:35:23.640 --> 00:35:24.640
 -- or that the larger
network will be an open place.

00:35:24.640 --> 00:35:28.749
So we do go into some detail to acknowledge
those, because while it's a

00:35:28.749 --> 00:35:29.749
convenience to make certain assumptions, it's
not fair to go forward

00:35:29.749 --> 00:35:34.869
without saying, gee, there are some substantial
threats.

00:35:34.869 --> 00:35:38.980
Net neutrality in the US and elsewhere is
a really, really big issue.

00:35:38.980 --> 00:35:43.230
I'm very concerned that it plays out in a
way that's fair to the people

00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:47.650
that build networks and fair to the people
that want to use networks.

00:35:47.650 --> 00:35:51.920
It's on a better path right now, today, than
it was 6 months ago,

00:35:51.920 --> 00:35:55.710
maybe, or two years ago.
But that's a threat.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:36:00.220
Maybe not getting enough of the network built
out is a threat, if

00:36:00.220 --> 00:36:02.390
mobile operators don't make swift and steady
moves toward 4G

00:36:02.390 --> 00:36:04.219
technologies, that drag their feet for whatever
reason.

00:36:04.219 --> 00:36:10.559
That's a threat.
There are a lot of things that could make

00:36:10.559 --> 00:36:17.009
our picture a little less
happy in the future than I what I described.

00:36:17.009 --> 00:36:19.230
Do you have a comment?

00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:22.609
&gt;&gt; I have a question.
So most of us are here today not because we

00:36:22.609 --> 00:36:25.829
don't have computers with
network access at home, but in order to have

00:36:25.829 --> 00:36:28.400
in-person interactions
with the other people here, right?

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:33.099
And people are kind of fundamentally social
in an in-person way, and I

00:36:33.099 --> 00:36:36.200
wanted to ask how you see that interacting
with the increased data

00:36:36.200 --> 00:36:37.200
access anywhere?

00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:40.329
Emily Nagle Green: Yeah, well I think back
to my concept,

00:36:40.329 --> 00:36:44.290
I'm waiting for somebody to invent four dimensional
smell-o-vision.

00:36:44.290 --> 00:36:47.979
I mean, that's my standard joke that, you
know, as long as there's

00:36:47.979 --> 00:36:51.029
squanderable abundance in the network, someone
will come up with

00:36:51.029 --> 00:36:55.760
something cool to do whether it's shipping
x-rays to India so they can

00:36:55.760 --> 00:36:59.420
be examined by less expensive medical staff
overnight, or, you know,

00:36:59.420 --> 00:37:02.970
creating something like YouTube.
I had a very, very early video conferencing

00:37:02.970 --> 00:37:07.599
system years ago when I
lived abroad and I led a group of people in

00:37:07.599 --> 00:37:09.839
Europe.
And we had one of those very early systems,

00:37:09.839 --> 00:37:15.470
and I was absolutely dogged
in my insistence that the company use it and

00:37:15.470 --> 00:37:17.339
that everybody be trained
on it.

00:37:17.339 --> 00:37:20.439
And it was stunningly difficult and painful
experience for all of us.

00:37:20.439 --> 00:37:24.564
And when I finally relented over my insistence
that we use it,

00:37:24.564 --> 00:37:28.229
everybody in the company took a huge sigh
of relief.

00:37:28.229 --> 00:37:31.829
Okay, Emily is not going to be a, you know,
video conferencing-manic

00:37:31.829 --> 00:37:37.059
person anymore.
But tele-presence experiences through things

00:37:37.059 --> 00:37:41.769
like the Cisco system that
a lot of people have experience with now are

00:37:41.769 --> 00:37:45.029
already dramatically
different than those early experiences.

00:37:45.029 --> 00:37:48.450
You can read the notes that people are taking
on another site.

00:37:48.450 --> 00:37:54.999
You can see the sweat on somebody's brow.
So even for things as important as face-to-face

00:37:54.999 --> 00:37:59.961
job interviews, they
are proving to be reasonable substitute, a

00:37:59.961 --> 00:38:02.940
substitute.
I think you look at what's happening there,

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:07.640
and you look at what's
happening in my old field, which is special

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:10.440
effects in the
entertainment business, and you look at the

00:38:10.440 --> 00:38:13.809
maturation of that
technology as evidenced by Avatar, you know,

00:38:13.809 --> 00:38:16.869
3-D and motion capture,
that makes the things that I worked on 20

00:38:16.869 --> 00:38:17.930
years ago look
extraordinarily primitive.

00:38:17.930 --> 00:38:22.799
So that's a long way of saying that while
none of those experiences are

00:38:22.799 --> 00:38:28.279
really a substitute for being in this room
 -- and apologies to the DVR

00:38:28.279 --> 00:38:32.880
participants -- I do think the substitutes
for being in face-to-face

00:38:32.880 --> 00:38:41.910
experience are going to gradually get better.
I don't know if that -- do you agree?

00:38:41.910 --> 00:38:46.970
&gt;&gt; I certainly agree they're getting better.
I remain undecided as to whether I think they

00:38:46.970 --> 00:38:49.509
will ever become good
enough that they're seen as an essentially

00:38:49.509 --> 00:38:51.869
perfect substitute or
whether there's something about being there

00:38:51.869 --> 00:38:54.200
in person some, some
ineffable something that people will always

00:38:54.200 --> 00:38:55.200
value.

00:38:55.200 --> 00:38:56.200
Emily Nagle Green: Yeah.
You might be right.

00:38:56.200 --> 00:39:00.960
You might be right.

00:39:00.960 --> 00:39:02.160
Comment?

00:39:02.160 --> 00:39:08.140
&gt;&gt; Yeah, just a question about when you talk
about the squanderable

00:39:08.140 --> 00:39:14.460
resource, I'm reminded of a comment that the,
you know, the high honcho

00:39:14.460 --> 00:39:18.960
at AT&amp;T made and then immediately regretted
about how, you know, 80

00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:21.910
percent of their network bandwidth was being
used by like one or two

00:39:21.910 --> 00:39:25.589
percent of their users and maybe we'll have
to go by pay by the

00:39:25.589 --> 00:39:30.450
megabyte pricing.
And certainly, at certain places, we take

00:39:30.450 --> 00:39:34.519
for granted that Wi-Fi is
available everywhere but you step outside

00:39:34.519 --> 00:39:39.599
of the high tech arena, and
you know, it's not.

00:39:39.599 --> 00:39:42.880
And I'm sort of curious, you know, especially
we do something like 4-D

00:39:42.880 --> 00:39:45.469
smell-o-vision, it's going to take a lot of
bandwidth.

00:39:45.469 --> 00:39:49.370
And there seems to be this hidden assumption
that a lot of us make, that

00:39:49.370 --> 00:39:53.759
eventually, we don't have to worry about bandwidth
or availability

00:39:53.759 --> 00:40:00.589
everywhere, that the model is pay 40 to 100
bucks a month, and you get

00:40:00.589 --> 00:40:03.960
all you can drink.
And do you believe that's a fair assumption,

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:06.369
and if not, what might
have to change?

00:40:06.369 --> 00:40:10.250
Emily Nagle Green: Well, the electrical industry
has been through

00:40:10.250 --> 00:40:15.630
this, right?
And we don't -- none of us believe that electricity

00:40:15.630 --> 00:40:20.960
should be free to
everyone, I don't think, if we took a poll.

00:40:20.960 --> 00:40:24.569
However, we do expect it to be everywhere,
and we do expect its cost to

00:40:24.569 --> 00:40:29.880
be minimal, and we expect other people to
bear the cost for us in

00:40:29.880 --> 00:40:35.660
places like airports and what not.
We don't expect to have to pay directly for

00:40:35.660 --> 00:40:38.140
electricity.
And as much as the network operators who make

00:40:38.140 --> 00:40:42.519
up, to be honest, a large
portion of my client base, so it's tough to

00:40:42.519 --> 00:40:45.190
 -- it's tough to say this
-- but, you know, one of the jobs of being

00:40:45.190 --> 00:40:48.529
an analyst is to speak truth
to power.

00:40:48.529 --> 00:40:51.749
It's tough for them to hear that analogy because
they don't like the

00:40:51.749 --> 00:40:57.690
idea that they will be as uninteresting and
as un-central to our future

00:40:57.690 --> 00:41:03.460
as a utility provider is, because that's just
not really a sexy

00:41:03.460 --> 00:41:04.799
business to be in.
And they want to be, you know, a much more

00:41:04.799 --> 00:41:07.369
central player in that
world.

00:41:07.369 --> 00:41:11.779
But I think we are moving towards a world
where connectivity, in order

00:41:11.779 --> 00:41:15.079
to be pervasive and in order to do all the
things we want it to do we

00:41:15.079 --> 00:41:18.870
will really demand economy in the provision
of that.

00:41:18.870 --> 00:41:23.229
But the problem that we have in the -- in
the progression towards that

00:41:23.229 --> 00:41:27.330
future is that we have a bunch of businesses
who are used to having a

00:41:27.330 --> 00:41:32.789
subscription relationship with you.
And so they, they're having to let go of the

00:41:32.789 --> 00:41:38.250
idea that every device
that you add isn't an opportunity for another

00:41:38.250 --> 00:41:44.019
bill to your house.
And they're having trouble thinking about

00:41:44.019 --> 00:41:48.329
how their business models can
shift to be very different than what they

00:41:48.329 --> 00:41:51.170
are today.
And the -- the near term thing that frustrates

00:41:51.170 --> 00:41:55.959
me the most some days is
that they're having a hard time moving towards

00:41:55.959 --> 00:41:58.640
different ways of
charging you for providing the service.

00:41:58.640 --> 00:42:01.989
I think a lot of us would be okay with the
more of something you

00:42:01.989 --> 00:42:05.780
consume, the more you should pay.
I don't think any of us think that's an unfair

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:10.700
economic principle, but
one of the problems with implementing it is

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:14.769
that a lot of consumers
don't understand what is a megabyte or a gigabyte.

00:42:14.769 --> 00:42:20.739
That's a bewildering unit of measurement.
So, you know, why shouldn't they be charging

00:42:20.739 --> 00:42:26.259
me for, you know downloading 20 songs or you
know what I song is.

00:42:26.259 --> 00:42:31.209
I have a sense of that entity.
And their move towards charging models that

00:42:31.209 --> 00:42:36.210
are simple for consumers to
understand and would allow them to feel less

00:42:36.210 --> 00:42:37.690
victimized by our
consumption.

00:42:37.690 --> 00:42:43.670
They're moving in that direction very slowly.
And I think that's a problem for them.

00:42:43.670 --> 00:43:08.750
And they may suffer the consequences of that
slow move.

00:43:08.750 --> 00:43:09.750
But it's in their hands.

00:43:09.750 --> 00:43:10.750
&gt;&gt; [inaudible]

00:43:10.750 --> 00:43:11.750
Emily Nagle Green: Oh, I would love to.
I thank you for the invitation.

00:43:11.750 --> 00:43:15.640
I was going to say one thing that, in closing.
The very last page of the book -- I think,

00:43:15.640 --> 00:43:17.770
I'm going to grab a copy and
read it.

00:43:17.770 --> 00:43:23.285
As I recall, it's the last or the next to
the last page of the book,

00:43:23.285 --> 00:43:28.900
there's a line in here.
I told you I met Steve Vinter last year, and

00:43:28.900 --> 00:43:33.229
I was almost finished with
the writing of the book.

00:43:33.229 --> 00:43:35.749
And on page 250, on the bottom it says, "I
met an executive recently

00:43:35.749 --> 00:43:39.400
who happened to mention that he left his old
job for a new position at

00:43:39.400 --> 00:43:42.869
Google because it offered him a chance to
change the world."

00:43:42.869 --> 00:43:49.049
That was Steve, and it stuck in my mind.
And I thought what a marvelous source of inspiration.

00:43:49.049 --> 00:43:52.089
And so I applaud you for all of you trying
to change the world, and I

00:43:52.089 --> 00:43:55.059
think the network that's emerging is going
to help a lot of other

00:43:55.059 --> 00:43:58.680
people to change the world as well.
Thanks for your attention.

00:43:58.680 --> 00:43:59.680
Thanks.

00:43:59.680 --> 00:43:59.681
[applause]

